## Combined Builds and Linked Code

The Enterprise Software may be imported, referenced, or otherwise
combined at build or runtime with code that is licensed under the
Nodaro Sustainable Use License set out in `LICENSE` (the **"Community
Software"**).

For the avoidance of doubt:

1. The terms of this Enterprise License apply to the Enterprise Software
   regardless of how it is packaged, bundled, compiled, transpiled,
   minified, or distributed. Compiling Enterprise Software together
   with Community Software into a single binary, container image,
   bundle, or other artifact does not relicense the Enterprise Software
   under the Nodaro Sustainable Use License, nor does it grant any
   production use rights to the Enterprise Software.

2. Any artifact (including, without limitation, Docker images, npm
   packages, compiled binaries, server bundles, and deployed instances)
   that **contains, links to, dynamically loads, or executes any portion
   of the Enterprise Software** is, with respect to that portion,
   subject to this Enterprise License and requires a valid Nodaro
   Enterprise license for production use.

3. Disabling, removing, or routing around the Enterprise Software at
   runtime does not by itself create a license to redistribute the
   Enterprise Software. To distribute an artifact under the Nodaro
   Sustainable Use License alone, the Enterprise Software must be
   removed from the artifact entirely.

4. The Community Software, when separated from the Enterprise Software
   and distributed without it, remains governed exclusively by the
   Nodaro Sustainable Use License.

5. A file that is otherwise Community Software but contains import
   statements, references, type declarations, or other syntactic
   dependencies that resolve to Enterprise Software does not, by virtue
   of those references alone, become Enterprise Software. However, any
   build, package, deployment, or executable artifact in which those
   references are actually resolved against Enterprise Software — such
   that the Enterprise Software is included in, loaded by, or executed
   as part of the artifact — falls within the scope of clauses 1
   through 3 above. To distribute Community Software under the Nodaro
   Sustainable Use License alone, you must either remove all such
   references or ensure that they resolve to non-Enterprise
   replacements at build time.

6. **Dormant Enterprise Software.** Notwithstanding anything to the
   contrary in this Enterprise License, including clauses 1 through 3
   above, deploying or running an artifact that contains Enterprise
   Software in production does not require a Nodaro Enterprise
   license, provided that both of the following are true:

   (a) no Enterprise license key is installed, entered, or activated
       in the deployment; and

   (b) no feature or functionality of the Enterprise Software is
       enabled or used.

   The mere presence, loading, or initialization of Enterprise
   Software within the artifact, and automated license-status checks
   performed by the software itself, do not by themselves constitute
   use of Enterprise features or functionality for the purposes of
   this clause.

   This exception grants production-use rights with respect to dormant
   Enterprise Software only. It does not permit redistribution of any
   artifact containing Enterprise Software, and it does not grant any
   rights to the Community Software contained in the same artifact —
   your use of the Community Software remains subject to, and requires
   rights under, the Nodaro Sustainable Use License.

## Patent Termination

If you initiate or participate in patent litigation against Nodaro LTD,
any other contributor, or any recipient of the Software (whether
Enterprise Software or Community Software) — including a cross-claim or
counterclaim in a lawsuit — alleging that the Software constitutes
direct or contributory patent infringement, then any rights granted to
you under this Enterprise License terminate as of the date the
litigation is filed.

